comments: Paul (GSW) brings his left forearm toward Williams (OKC) and marginal contact occurs during the driving shot attempt.
Green (GSW) firms up over to his left leg in Dort's (OKC) path and incidental foot-to-foot contact occurs during the pick.

After communicating with the Replay Center, it is deemed that Green (GSW) is in a normal shooting motion when contact occurs with Holmgren (OKC) and there is no hostile act on the play.  Play resumes with Golden State given possession of the ball.
Curry (GSW) is moving alongside Giddey's (OKC) path and marginal body contact occurs as they come together at the end of the drive.
Giddey (OKC) brings his left hand underneath the ball before resuming his dribble.
The game is stopped due to a shot clock malfunction. After correcting the clock, the game resumes with the Warriors retaining possession of the ball.
Holmgren (OKC) jumps alongside Curry's (GSW) path and marginal body contact occurs during the driving shot attempt.
After Thompson (GSW) gains possession of the loose ball, Williams moves forward into him and initiates contact that causes him to fall to the floor.
Green (GSW) briefly places his hands on Holmgren (OKC) as he begins his drive on the perimeter but the contact is marginal.

Replay review of the foul called on Green (GSW) pursuant to a coach's challenge was deemed unsuccessful. Green is late to the spot and does not establish a legal guarding position in Holmgren's (OKC) path before contact.
Payton II (GSW) establishes himself in Dort's (OKC) path and does not deliver illegal contact.
Joe (OKC) firms up in a screening position in Wiggins' (GSW) path and the contact is marginal as he leans forward.
Green (GSW) extends his right arm to initiate contact with Dort's (OKC) body, which affects his shot attempt near the rim.

After communicating with the Replay Center, the ruling on the floor of offensive basket interference is overturned. There is clear and conclusive evidence that Green (GSW) does not touch the ball and -- although Green makes contact with the rim -- contacting the rim, standing alone, does not violate the rule.  In order for contact with the rim to constitute offensive basket interference when the ball is not in the net, it must (a) occur while the ball is sitting or rolling on the rim and using the rim as its lower base, (b) cause the ball to take an unnatural bounce, or (c) move the rim off-center.  None of those conditions were satisfied on this play, so there was no basket interference.
